India's New Hope
The US Cambridge - India Election may be the most important positive economic event of 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress Party, which has almost always ruled India since India's independence from Britain in 1947.
They may be happy with this decision.
The Congress Party leader and former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's widow, Sonia Gandhi, has been de facto ruler since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh is only a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued a populist agenda, increased transfers, and led to India's economic growth rate to fall below 4% in 2013.
The per capita GDP still hovers around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi promised to bring rapid growth in employment and income for all of India, just like when he was the Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat has become a business-friendly state, with economic activities expanded, attracting domestic and foreign business investments.
One of the key features of the latest election is that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) gained an absolute majority in the National Parliament, which can be said to be unprecedented in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
The two key officials will assist Modi in economic planning.
New Finance Minister Arun Jaitley has rich political experience, having served as a minister in the previous Bharatiya Janata Party government.
Jaitely is also known for his sympathetic strategic thoughts towards business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India. Rajan is an outstanding economist, and during his tenure as Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, he showed his desire to lower India's double-digit inflation rate and try to reform some of the inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
Measures to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and show results.
However, to find out if the new government is taking action towards faster long-term growth, you should look at the progress in these ten policy areas.
Education.
Despite India having excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small proportion of people are able to access opportunities provided by these institutions because primary and secondary education in India is very backward.
Only 60% of Indian adults have literacy skills at the primary level.
Teachers themselves have inadequate educational background, and their working motivation is also inadequate, and many teachers never appear at the schools where they work.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products across the country and around the world.
Recent expansion of private airlines and airports shows that private enterprises can also achieve in this field.
Fiscal integration.
Large-scale budget deficits are absorbing national savings, which could otherwise be used to expand business investment. The budget deficits have also led to an increase in national debt that can only be financed by future tax revenue.
Privatization.
The government-owned manufacturing and other industrial enterprises in India are inefficient, often resulting in consuming national savings.
Selling these enterprises can directly help to accelerate economic growth.
Eliminate subsidies.
Electricity and energy subsidies have led to wasteful overconsumption and an increase in fiscal deficit.
Although it is difficult to abolish these subsidies politically, they should be replaced with cash transfer payments. Currently, with the introduction of fingerprint-based cash transfer systems, the efficiency of cash transfer payments in India has been greatly improved.
Reform of agriculture.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
As a result, a large quantity of goods are stockpiled in warehouses, while the incentives for production are misled.
Agricultural markets should be privatized.
Property rights and regional zoning.
As long as you've visited Mumbai or other large Indian cities, you will see that regional zoning restrictions have led to poor use of urban land, limiting the pace of urbanization.
Lack of clear property rights, particularly land rights for agricultural land, has hindered industrialization in rural areas.
Relax restrictions on foreign investment.
Currently, foreign companies are unable to become majority shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions can strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex system of national and state sales tax distorts domestic trade.
The debate on replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a dual tax system has been going on for a long time, and now it should enter the implementation stage.
Corruption.
High-level corruption cases have destroyed people's confidence in the economy and interfered with officials' decision-making.
India is also plagued by small-scale corruption, bribery has become a common feature in all commercial and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and limit small-scale corruption through new cash transfer payment systems.
The Indian stock market has risen by 20% this year, driven by the expectation of rapid growth and increased profits.
Now, Modi and the Bharatiya Janata Party need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their election campaign commitments.
